         b'                \n\n\n<div id="col2" class="events">\n\n    <h3 s'
         b'tyle="text-align: center; padding-left: 5px; margin-bottom: 0px; pad'
         b'ding-bottom: 5px; border-bottom: 2px solid  #93A445;"><a href="/even'
         b'ts">Upcoming Events</a></h3>\n\nNo upcoming events.\n\n</div>\n<d'
         b'iv id="description">\n<img src="/static/images/csml_logo.jpg" alt'
         b'="CSML Logo">\n<p style="margin-top: 20px">\nThe Centre for Comput'
         b'ational Statistics and Machine Learning (CSML)\nspans three depar'
         b'tments at University College London, \n<a href="http://www.cs.ucl'
         b'.ac.uk">Computer Science</a>, \n<a href="http://www.ucl.ac.uk/sta'
         b'tistics">Statistical Science</a>, \nand the <a href="http://www.g'
         b'atsby.ucl.ac.uk">Gatsby Computational\n    Neuroscience Unit</a>.'
         b'\n</p>\n<p>\nThe Centre pioneers an emerging field that\nbrings toge'
         b'ther statistics, the recent extensive advances in\ntheoretically '
         b'well-founded machine learning, and links with a broad\nrange of a'
         b'pplication areas drawn from across the college, including\nneuros'
         b'cience, astrophysics, biological sciences, complexity science,\ne'
         b'tc. There is a deliberate intention to maintain and cultivate a\n'
         b'plurality of approaches within the centre including Bayesian,\nfr'
         b'equentist, on-line, statistical, etc.\n</p>\n<p> If you are not al'
         b'ready a member and would like to sign up to the <a href="http://www.'
         b'mailinglists.ucl.ac.uk/mailman/listinfo/csml">mailing list</a>, you '
         b'can do so at \n<a href="http://www.mailinglists.ucl.ac.uk/mailman'
         b'/listinfo/csml">this link</a> (please provide your name and affiliat'
         b'ion when signing up to the mailing list).\n</p>\n\n</div>\n\n<div'
         b' class="newscontainer">\n<h2 style="border-bottom: 3px solid #93A'
         b'445; margin-top: 20px;"><a href="/news/">News</a></h2>\n\n<div cla'
         b'ss="news">\n<h3><a href="/news/2015-06-03-csml-master-class-carlo'
         b's-guestrin-and-e">CSML Master Class with Carlos Guestrin (additional'
         b' talk by Emily Fox)</a></h3>\n<p>\nWe are pleased to announce that'
         b' the next CSML Master Class, sponsored by Google Deepmind, will take'
         b' place from 2-3 July 2015. Carlos Guestrin (University of Washington'
         b') will give two talks, with an additional talk being given by Emily '
         b'Fox (University of Washington).\r\n<br /><br />\r\nFurther details a'
         b're available at <a href="http://www.csml.ucl.ac.uk/events/series/21"'
         b'>http://www.csml.ucl.ac.uk/events/series/21</a>.\n</p>\n\n</div'
         b'>\n\n<div class="news">\n<h3><a href="/news/2014-10-20-next-csml-ma'
         b'ster-class-regsitration-ope">Next CSML Master Class with Sham Kakade'
         b' - registration open!</a></h3>\n<p>\nSham Kakade from Microsoft Re'
         b'search New England will be giving the next CSML Master Class from 3 '
         b"- 5 November 2014. The topic of the Master Class will be 'Some Algor"
         b"ithmic Questions in Statistics: Estimation and Optimization'. \r\n"
         b'<br /><br />\r\nPlease see the events pages for full details and a'
         b' link to register <br />\r\n<a href="http://www.csml.ucl.ac.uk/eve'
         b'nts/series/20">http://www.csml.ucl.ac.uk/events/series/20</a>.\n<'
         b'/p>\n\n</div>\n\n<div class="news">\n<h3><a href="/news/2014-08-1'
         b'7-ucl-team-uclstats-win-rss-challenge-201">UCL team UCLStats win RSS'
         b' challenge 2014 !</a></h3>\n<p>\nUCL team "UCLStats" of Beate Fran'
         b'ke, Alfredo Kalaitzis, Sam Livingstone and Michael Betancourt are th'
         b'e Overall Winners of the Royal Statistical Society Statistical Analy'
         b'tics challenge 2014, organized by The Young Statisticians Section & '
         b'Research Section of the Royal Statistical Society, sponsored by Sele'
         b'ct Statistics. The team will be invited to present their findings at'
         b' the YSS and Research Section Statistical Analytics Challenge Sessio'
         b'n at the RSS 2014 conference in Sheffield on Wednesday 3rd September'
         b' 2014. \r\n<br /><br />\r\nThe 2014 competition was designed to anal'
         b'yse some data from Neuroimaging, namely resting state functional MRI'
         b' data. Unlike many data prediction competitions, there was no right '
         b'answer here (at least not one that is known), but care in the statis'
         b'tical analysis was the focus of the challenge. The title of the UCLS'
         b'tats submission was "Long Range Spatio-Temporal Dependence in fMRI I'
         b'maging Data". \r\n\n</p>\n\n</div>\n\n<div class="news">\n<h3><a hre'
         b'f="/news/2014-06-25-next-csml-master-class-shai-ben-david-r">Next CS'
         b'ML Master Class with Shai Ben-David - Registration now open!</a></h3'
         b'>\n<p>\nThe next CSML Master Class will be given by Shai Ben-David'
         b' from University of Waterloo. The talks will take place from 21-23 J'
         b'uly 2014, and registration is now open. Full details are available a'
         b't <a href="http://www.csml.ucl.ac.uk/events/master_classes">http://w'
         b'ww.csml.ucl.ac.uk/events/master_classes</a>.\n</p>\n\n</div>\n\n<'
         b'div class="news">\n<h3><a href="/news/2014-06-04-data-science-pos'
         b'ition-bristol">Data Science Position in Bristol</a></h3>\n<p>\nRes'
         b'earch Assistant in Data Science<br />\r\n(Full time - Closing date'
         b' for applications - 17-Jun-2014)<br />\r\n<a href="http://www.jobs'
         b'.ac.uk/job/AIS432/research-assistant-in-data-science/">http://www.jo'
         b'bs.ac.uk/job/AIS432/research-assistant-in-data-science/</a>\r\n<br'
         b' /><br />\r\nWe are looking for an outstanding data scientist to j'
         b'oin the ERC\r\nproject "ThinkBIG" (led by Nello Cristianini). You '
         b'will contribute to\r\nextend a pre-existing software infrastructur'
         b'e for the analysis of\r\nlarge corpora. This is a position for an '
         b'experienced data scientist\r\nwith a strong background in a STEM f'
         b'ield, and research training, with\r\nexperience in statistical mac'
         b'hine learning applied to textual data,\r\nand in scaling software '
         b'for big-data applications.\r\n<br /><br />\r\nIn addition to your on'
         b'line application, you will need to submit a\r\nsample of code (pre'
         b'ferably Java) written by you which shows your best\r\nwork in the '
         b'creation of reusable, maintainable code in a group\r\nenvironment.'
         b' Please select a sample no larger than 5 classes. This\r\nsample o'
         b'f code does not necessarily need to be related to text mining.\r\n'
         b'<br /><br />\r\nPlease send the sample of code (alone) to Tom Welf'
         b'are at:\r\ncode.for.vacancy(at)gmail.com with a short explanation.'
         b' Please do not\r\nsend any enquiries to this email address.\r\n<br /'
         b'><br />\r\n\r\nInformal enquiries can be made to Nello Cristiani'
         b'ni:\r\nnello.cristianini(at)bristol.ac.uk.\r\n<br /><br />\r\nIt i'
         b's expected that interviews will be held in late June 2014.\r\n<br '
         b'/><br />\r\nThinkBIG page: <a href="http://thinkbig.enm.bris.ac.uk'
         b'/">http://thinkbig.enm.bris.ac.uk/</a>\r\n<br /><br />\r\nPlease che'
         b'ck all details and specific requirements:\r\n<a href="http://www.j'
         b'obs.ac.uk/job/AIS432/research-assistant-in-data-science/">http://www'
         b'.jobs.ac.uk/job/AIS432/research-assistant-in-data-science/</a>\r\n'
         b'\r\n\r\n\n</p>\n\n</div>\n\n<div class="news">\n<h3><a href="/news'
         b'/2014-03-10-next-csml-master-class-registration-now">Next CSML Maste'
         b'r Class - Registration now open!</a></h3>\n<p>\nThe next CSML Mast'
         b'er Class will be given by Andrew Gelman from Columbia University. Th'
         b'e talks will take place from 14-16 April 2014, and registration is n'
         b'ow open. Full details are available at <a href="http://www.csml.ucl.'
         b'ac.uk/events/master_classes">http://www.csml.ucl.ac.uk/events/master'
         b'_classes</a>.\n</p>\n\n</div>\n\n<div class="news">\n<h3><a href="'
         b'/news/2014-01-20-postdoc-position-involving-pathbreaking">Postdoc po'
         b'sition involving pathbreaking work in MRP, Stan, and the 2014 electi'
         b'on!</a></h3>\n<p>\nThe below vacancy in the Applied Statistics Cen'
         b'ter at Columbia University may be of interest to CSML members \r\n'
         b'<br /><br />\r\nWe\xe2\x80\x99re working with polling company YouGo'
         b'v to track public opinion, state-by-state and district-by-district, '
         b'during the 2014 campaign. We\xe2\x80\x99ll be using multilevel re'
         b'gression and poststratification, and implementing it in Stan, and de'
         b'veloping the necessary new parts of Stan to get this running scalabl'
         b'y and efficiently. And we\xe2\x80\x99ll be making the most detail'
         b'ed, up-to-date election forecasts. \r\n<br /><br />\r\nWhat you\xe2'
         b'\x80\x99ll be doing if you join us as a postdoc: \r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Y'
         b'ou\xe2\x80\x99ll be in the midst of the most advanced polling tea'
         b'm anywhere;</li>\r\n<li>You\xe2\x80\x99ll be doing cutting-edge sta'
         b'tistical research on MRP with deep interactions; </li>\r\n<li>'
         b'You\xe2\x80\x99ll be doing basic research in statistical computin'
         b'g, developing fast and scalable deterministic and stochastic algorit'
         b'hms for fitting multilevel models; </li>\r\n<li>You\xe2\x80\x99ll b'
         b'e working inside Stan, the most advanced general computational frame'
         b'work for Bayesian analysis. We\xe2\x80\x99re doing research, not '
         b'just implementing existing methods. </li>\r\n</ul><br />\r\nWhat we '
         b'need: \r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Stats knowledge. You should know your way arou'
         b'nd Bayesian data analysis;</li>\r\n<li>Serious computing skills. Y'
         b'ou should be a skilled C++ programmer;</li>\r\n<li>Interest in the'
         b' application area. You should care about public opinion, and it shou'
         b'ld be important to you that our forecasts are good. When our estimat'
         b'es of opinion for some group in the population don\xe2\x80\x99t m'
         b'ake sense, you should notice and be bothered by it.</li> \r\n</ul>'
         b'<br />\r\n\r\nWe have a great team with diverse skills (computing, s'
         b'tatistics, political science) that plays nicely together and from wh'
         b'om you can learn a lot. Also lots of opportunity to collaborate with'
         b' researchers in many different quantitative disciplines through Colu'
         b'mbia\xe2\x80\x99s Applied Statistics Center. \r\n<br /><br />\r\n'
         b'The position is a 2-year postdoc, funded by Yougov and situated in t'
         b'he Applied Statistics Center at Columbia University. More details on'
         b' the position can be found at <a href="http://andrewgelman.com/2014/'
         b'01/15/postdoc-involving-pathbreaking-work-mrp-stan-2014-election/ ">'
         b'http://andrewgelman.com/2014/01/15/postdoc-involving-pathbreaking-wo'
         b'rk-mrp-stan-2014-election/ </a>.\n</p>\n\n</div>\n\n<div class="n'
         b'ews">\n<h3><a href="/news/2013-11-20-internships-amazon">Internsh'
         b'ips at Amazon</a></h3>\n<p>\nThe Amazon Machine Learning Science T'
         b'eam is seeking interns to join the Scalable Machine Learning, Foreca'
         b'sting, Content Linkage, and Computer Vision groups in Berlin, German'
         b'y. We focus on data-driven approaches in these areas for Amazon as a'
         b' whole as well as their applications to particular products.  \r\n'
         b'\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>In the Forecasting group, we develop sophisticated a'
         b'lgorithms that involve learning from very large amounts of data, suc'
         b'h as prices, promotions, similar products, and a product'
         b'\xe2\x80\x99s attributes, in order to forecast the demand of over'
         b' 10 million products. These forecasts are used to automatically orde'
         b'r more than $200 million worth of inventory weekly, establish labor '
         b'plans for over 10,000 employees, and predict the overall company'
         b'\xe2\x80\x99s financial performance. The work is complex and impo'
         b'rtant to Amazon. The better our forecasts, the more we can lower pri'
         b'ces for customers and offer in-stock selection.</li>\r\n<li>In the'
         b' Content Linkage group, our goal is to learn to dynamically link dig'
         b'ital content on Amazon and the Web, so that customers can discover f'
         b'resh and related content relevant to books and other media they purc'
         b'hase. Our other task is to enable fast and scalable translation of A'
         b"mazon's product catalog, customer reviews and other natural language"
         b' data across a large number of language pairs.</li>\r\n<li>In the '
         b'Computer Vision group our goal is to develop real-time object recogn'
         b'ition and object tracking algorithms that can distinguish between 10'
         b"+M products and can be used to automate Amazon's fulfillment and pro"
         b'duct quality systems. The more accurately we can detect products, th'
         b'e more we can speed-up the delivery to customers.</li>\r\n<li>In t'
         b'he Scalable Machine Learning group, we develop learning algorithms a'
         b'ble to handle the gigantic data volumes collected by Amazon and able'
         b' to operate at internet speed. We explore new paradigms for distribu'
         b'ted optimisation and inference. We also investigate efficient repres'
         b'entations of very large and complex data models. Finally, we automat'
         b'e the process of building and learning data models to enable evidenc'
         b'e-driven decision-making with minimal effort from the domain experts'
         b'.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\nAs an intern, you will have an opportunity '
         b'to work on complex mathematical problems with a large element of unc'
         b'ertainty. You will develop new scalable algorithms and improve exist'
         b'ing approaches based on modern statistical, machine learning, and da'
         b'ta mining methods to impact the core business of Amazon. You are an '
         b'individual with outstanding analytical abilities and excellent commu'
         b'nication skills. You will be responsible for researching, developing'
         b', and analyzing statistical models. You will also be prototyping the'
         b' implementations by using high-level modelling languages such as MAT'
         b'LAB or R, or in software languages such as Java, or C++. You should '
         b'have a strong background in machine learning with domain knowledge a'
         b'nd experience in the following areas: data-driven statistical modell'
         b'ing, graphical models, feature extraction and analysis, supervised l'
         b'earning (in particular, discriminative methods). You should have at '
         b'least one refereed academic publications in these areas.\r\n<br />'
         b'<br />\r\nPlease contact Cedric Archambeau cedrica(at)amazon.de if'
         b' you are interested in this opportunity.\r\n\n</p>\n\n</div>\n\n<di'
         b'v class="news">\n<h3><a href="/news/2013-10-07-connectionists-cal'
         b'l-participation-mlss-">Connectionists: Call for Participation: MLSS '
         b'Machine Learning Summer School, Reykjavik, April 25 - M</a></h3>'
         b'\n<p>\nColocated with AISTATS 2014, the Seventeenth International '
         b'Conference on\r\nArtificial Intelligence and Statistics\r\n\r\n<p>'
         b'\r\n\r\nThe Machine Learning Summer School will take place at Reykja'
         b'vik University\r\nin Reykjavik, Iceland, from April 25 to May 4, 2'
         b'014. The field of machine \r\nlearning is at the intersection of c'
         b'omputer science, statistics, mathematics,\r\nand optimization. The'
         b' Machine Learning Summer School (MLSS) is a great venue\r\nfor gra'
         b'duate students, researchers, and professionals to learn about\r\nf'
         b'undamental and advanced methods of machine learning, data analysis, '
         b'and\r\ninference, from theory to practice.<p>\r\n\r\n<p>The MLSS i'
         b'n Reykjavik features an exciting program with talks from leading'
         b'\r\nexperts in the field. MLSS is colocated with the high-profile '
         b'international\r\nconference AISTATS 2014, the Seventeenth Internat'
         b'ional Conference on\r\nArtificial Intelligence and Statistics. The'
         b' MLSS also features a poster\r\nsession for students, jointly with'
         b' a poster session of AISTATS.<p>\r\n\r\n<p>Limited travel support fo'
         b'r students is available, see the website for\r\ndetails.<p>\r\n\n'
         b'</p>\n\n</div>\n\n<div class="news">\n<h3><a href="/news/2013-08-'
         b'09-uk-computational-statistics-researcher-">UK Computational Statist'
         b'ics Researcher wins ISBA Mitchell Prize</a></h3>\n<p>\n<p>\r\n<a hre'
         b'f="http://www.ucl.ac.uk/statistics/people/ioannamanolopoulou">Dr Ioa'
         b'nna Manolopoulou</a> and her research collaborators have been awarde'
         b'd the 2012 <a href="http://bayesian.org/awards/MitchellPrize.html">M'
         b'itchell Prize</a> by the International Society for Bayesian Analysis'
         b' for their paper "<a href="http://www.tandfonline.com/doi/full/10.10'
         b'80/01621459.2012.655995#.UgUAKOaaHrF">Bayesian Spatio-Dynamic Modell'
         b'ing in Cell Motility Studies: Learning Nonlinear Taxic Fields Guidin'
         b'g Immune Response</a>" for its sophisticated development of model-ba'
         b'sed inference methods in the expanding field of immune-cell dynamics'
         b'.\r\n</p>\r\n\r\n<p>\r\nThe Mitchell Prize is awarded annually in re'
         b'cognition of an outstanding paper that describes how a Bayesian anal'
         b'ysis has solved an important applied problem.\r\n</p>\n</p>\n\n</'
         b'div>\n\n<div class="news">\n<h3><a href="/news/2013-08-01-csml-host'
         b'-meeting-variable-selection-an">CSML host meeting on  variable selec'
         b'tion and dimension reduction in clustering and classification</a></h'
         b'3>\n<p>\n<p>\r\nOn 8-9 November 2013 there will be a joint meeting o'
         b'f the British Classification Society (BCS) and the working group on '
         b'data analysis and numerical classification (AG DANK) at the Departme'
         b'nt of Statistical Science, UCL. The meeting is supported by the Cent'
         b're of Computational Statistics and Machine Learning (CSML). The loca'
         b'l organiser is Dr Christian Hennig.\r\n</p>\r\n\r\n<p>\r\nFocus topi'
         b'c of the meeting is "Variable selection and dimension reduction in c'
         b'lustering and classification".\r\n</p>\r\n\r\n<p>\r\nThere will be t'
         b'hree invited speakers: Gilles Celeux, Paris; Mario Figueiredo, Lisbo'
         b'n; and Roberto Rocci, Rome.\r\n</p>\r\n\r\n<p>\r\nUp to date informa'
         b'tion on the meeting including deadlines and contact details can be f'
         b'ound on\r\n<a href="http://www.homepages.ucl.ac.uk/~ucakche/agdank'
         b'/agdankht2013.html">here</a>.\r\n</p>\n</p>\n\n</div>\n\n<div class'
         b'="news">\n<h3><a href="/news/2013-05-22-dr-christian-hennig-speak'
         b'-presidents-in">Dr Christian Hennig to speak in the president&#39;s '
         b'invited session at IFCS 2013, Tilburg</a></h3>\n<p>\n<p>\r\nDr Chris'
         b'tian Hennig was invited by the president of the International Federa'
         b'tion of Classification Societies (IFCS), Iven van Mechelen, to give '
         b'a presentation on "Measurement of quality in cluster analysis" in th'
         b"e president's invited session at the IFCS 2013 conference in Tilburg"
         b', the Netherlands, 15-17 July 2013. Dr Hennig will give further invi'
         b'ted presentations on the same topic at the Summer Working Group on M'
         b'ixture Models, Bologna, 22-26 July and the ISI conference in Hong Ko'
         b'ng, 26-30 August. Dr Hennig was also invited to the ERCIM conference'
         b' 2013 in London, 14-16 December (title to be announced).\r\n</p>\n<'
         b'/p>\n\n</div>\n\n<div class="news">\n<h3><a href="/news/2013-05-2'
         b'2-dr-christian-hennig-awarded-eprsc-stand">Dr Christian Hennig award'
         b'ed EPRSC standard research grant</a></h3>\n<p>\n<p>\r\nDr Christian '
         b'Hennig was awarded an EPSRC standard research grant for work on "A m'
         b'ulticriterion approach to cluster validation".  In this research, Dr'
         b' Hennig will look at the notoriously difficult problem of estimating'
         b' the number of clusters from a fresh angle, connecting criteria prop'
         b'erly to different research aims. The project includes collaborations'
         b' with the robust clustering group of the University of Valladolid le'
         b'd by Prof Carlos Matran, the expert for biological species delimitat'
         b'ion Dr Bernhard Hausdorf, University of Hamburg, the IFCS cluster be'
         b'nchmarking initiative led by IFCS president Prof Iven van Mechelen, '
         b"KU Leuven and Dr Hennig's former PhD student Dr Pietro Coretto, Univ"
         b'ersity of Salerno.\r\n</p>\n</p>\n\n</div>\n\n<div class="news">\n<h'
         b'3><a href="/news/2013-02-22-epsrc-grant-advanced-stochastic-computa"'
         b'>EPSRC grant for Advanced Stochastic Computation for Inference from '
         b'Tree, Graph and Network Models</a></h3>\n<p>\n<p>PI: M. De Iorio; '
         b'CO-I A. Beskos, D. Balding, A. Jasra </p>\r\n\r\n<p>The main objecti'
         b've is to develop and characterise principled approximations to compl'
         b'ex statistical models.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The research work aims to reduc'
         b'e both the variance of simulation-based estimates, and the computati'
         b'onal time of stochastic algorithms. This will facilitate the impleme'
         b'ntation of stochastic models in real biological applications. The gr'
         b'ant will support a postdoctoral researcher for three years.</p>\r'
         b'\n\n</p>\n\n</div>\n\n<div class="news">\n<h3><a href="/news/2013-0'
         b'2-22-epsrc-grant-funding-gabriel-brostow-mar">EPSRC grant funding fo'
         b'r Gabriel Brostow, Mark Girolami and Kate Jones (#EP/K015664/1)</a><'
         b'/h3>\n<p>\n<p>Funded by EPSRC for 3 years</p>\r\n\r\n<p>ENGAGE: In'
         b'teractive Machine Learning Accelerating Progress in Science, An Emer'
         b'ging Theme of ICT Research In short, it brings together Machine Lear'
         b'ning, Computer Vision, Human-Computer Interaction, and Biodiversity '
         b'Science to help cope with the global extinction crisis. </p>\r\n\r\n'
         b"<p>The PI's on the project are:<br>\r\nGabriel Brostow - UCL CS<br"
         b'>\r\nMark Girolami - UCL Stats<br>\r\nKate Jones - UCL Department of'
         b' Genetics, Evolution and Environment Mike Terry - University of Wate'
         b'rloo, CS and ZSL Chair, Ecology and Biodiversity</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Our v'
         b'ision is to establish and lead a new theme in ICT research based on '
         b'Interactive Machine Learning (IML). Our expansion of IML will give s'
         b'cientists and non-ICT specialists unprecedented access to cutting-ed'
         b'ge Machine Learning algorithms by providing a humancomputer interfac'
         b'e by which they can directly interact with large scale data and comp'
         b'uting resources in an intuitive visual environment. In addition, the'
         b' outcome of this particular project will have a direct transformativ'
         b'e impact on the sciences by making it possible for non-programming i'
         b'ndividuals (scientists), to create systems that semi-automatically d'
         b'etect objects and events in vast quantities of A) audio and B) visua'
         b'l data.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>By working together across two parallel, highl'
         b'y interconnected streams of ICT research, we will develop the founda'
         b'tions of statistical methodology, algorithms and systems for IML. As'
         b' an exemplar, this project partners with world leading scientists gr'
         b'appling with the challenge of analysing enormous quantities of heter'
         b'ogeneous data being generated in Biodiversity Science.</p>\r\n\n</p'
         b'>\n\n</div>\n\n<div class="news">\n<h3><a href="/news/2012-12-18-'
         b'i-opening-workshop-31-january-2013-210p">i-like Opening workshop - 3'
         b'1 January 2013, 2:10pm to 5:30pm</a></h3>\n<p>\n<p>Please go to <a'
         b" href='http://www.i-like.org.uk/launch-day-31st-january-2013.html'>h"
         b'ttp://www.i-like.org.uk/launch-day-31st-january-2013.html</a> for de'
         b'tails of this event.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The day is principally aimed at p'
         b'hd and post doc level, although others are more than welcome to atte'
         b'nd as well.</p>\r\n\n</p>\n\n</div>\n\n<div class="news">\n<h3><a hr'
         b'ef="/news/faculty_Gatsby">Faculty Member In Machine Learning Or Stat'
         b'istics</a></h3>\n<p>\n<p>The Gatsby Computational Neuroscience Uni'
         b't at University College London is looking to recruit a junior or sen'
         b'ior level faculty member in machine learning or statistics. We espec'
         b'ially seek candidates who work in probabilistic or statistical machi'
         b'ne learning.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The closing date for applications is 20 D'
         b'ecember 2012</p>\r\n\r\n<p>For further information, please see <a hr'
         b"ef='http://www.gatsby.ucl.ac.uk/vacancies/FacultyJD.pdf'>www.gatsby."
         b'ucl.ac.uk/vacancies/FacultyJD.pdf</a></p>\n</p>\n\n</div>\n\n<div'
         b' class="news">\n<h3><a href="/news/2012-09-26-professor-mark-giro'
         b'lami-awarded-epsrc-f">Professor Mark Girolami awarded EPSRC funding '
         b'to lead UK research network on computational statistic</a></h3>\n'
         b'<p>\nEPSRC are providing three years of funding to establish and '
         b'build a UK wide research network on Computational Statistics and Mac'
         b'hine Learning. This network will be led by the UCL Centre of Computa'
         b'tional Statistics and Machine Learning (www.csml.ucl.ac.uk).\r\n\r\n'
         b'Website <a href="http://gow.epsrc.ac.uk/NGBOViewGrant.aspx?GrantRef='
         b'EP/K009788/1">http://gow.epsrc.ac.uk/NGBOViewGrant.aspx?GrantRef=EP/'
         b'K009788/1</a>\r\n\n</p>\n\n</div>\n\n<div class="news">\n<h3><a href'
         b'="/news/2012-08-21-dr-simon-byrne-awarded-epsrc-fellowship">Dr Simon'
         b' Byrne awarded EPSRC Fellowship</a></h3>\n<p>\nDr Simon Byrne has '
         b'been awarded a Post-Doctoral Fellowship from the Engineering and Phy'
         b'sical Sciences Research Council (EPSRC) for his project entitled "In'
         b'formation geometry for Bayesian hierarchical models". This will prov'
         b'ide support for three years, with the aim of developing both theoret'
         b'ical understanding of the geometric structure of hierarchical models'
         b', as well as practical computational tools to make these models feas'
         b'ible for larger and more complex problems.\n</p>\n\n</div>\n\n<di'
         b'v class="news">\n<h3><a href="/news/2012-06-27-dcse-funding">dCSE'
         b' Funding Awarded To Ben Calderhead and Mark Girolami</a></h3>\n<p'
         b'>\n<a href="/people/calderhead">Dr Ben Calderhead</a>, Research F'
         b'ellow in CoMPLEX, and <a href="/people/girolami">Professor Mark\r'
         b'\nGirolami</a>, Director of CSML, have been awarded <a href="http'
         b'://www.hector.ac.uk/cse/distributedcse">dCSE funding</a> from <a hre'
         b'f="http://www.epsrc.ac.uk/">EPSRC</a> and\r\n<a href="http://www.n'
         b'ag.co.uk/">The Numerical Algorithms Group (NAG)</a> to employ a soft'
         b'ware developer for 1\r\nyear for an ambitious plan to develop high'
         b'ly parallelised code\r\nimplementing differential geometric MCMC s'
         b'tatistical methodology for\r\ncluster computers in UCL, and for <a'
         b' href="http://www.hector.ac.uk/">HECToR</a>, the national supercompu'
         b'ter.\n</p>\n\n</div>\n\n<div class="news">\n<h3><a href="/news/201'
         b'2-04-02-epsrc-grants-fellowships">EPSRC Grants and Fellowships Award'
         b'ed to CSML Members</a></h3>\n<p>\n<p>Professor <a href="/people/gi'
         b'rolami">Mark Girolami</a>, Director of CSML, has been awarded an EPS'
         b'RC Established Career Research Fellowship: "<a href="http://gow.epsr'
         b'c.ac.uk/NGBOViewGrant.aspx?GrantRef=EP%2FJ016934%2F1">Advancing the '
         b'Geometric Framework for Computational Statistics: Theory, Methodolog'
         b'y and Modern Day Applications</a>". Furthermore, three members of CS'
         b'ML have been awarded EPSRC grants supporting their research projects'
         b':\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><a href="/people/beskos">Alex Beskos: <a href="http'
         b'://gow.epsrc.ac.uk/NGBOViewGrant.aspx?GrantRef=EP%2FJ01365X%2F1">Seq'
         b'uential Monte Carlo methods for applications in high dimensions</a><'
         b'/li>\r\n<li><a href="/people/nelson">James Nelson: <a href="http:/'
         b'/gow.epsrc.ac.uk/NGBOViewGrant.aspx?GrantRef=EP%2FJ010081%2F1">Multi'
         b'resolution Markov Models for Detecting Radial Patterns of Spicules i'
         b'n Mammograms</a></li>\r\n<li><a href="/people/silva">Ricardo Silva'
         b': <a href="http://gow.epsrc.ac.uk/NGBOViewGrant.aspx?GrantRef=EP%2FJ'
         b'013293%2F1">Learning Highly Structured Sparse Latent Variable Models'
         b'</a></li>\r\n</ul>\n</p>\n\n</div>\n\n<div class="news">\n<h3><a hre'
         b'f="/news/2012-03-28-csml-facebook-twitter">CSML on Facebook and Twit'
         b'ter</a></h3>\n<p>\nCSML now has a <a href="http://www.facebook.com'
         b'/uclcsml">Facebook page</a> and a <a href="https://twitter.com/#!/uc'
         b'lcsml">Twitter account</a> where news and events are announced. So l'
         b'ike <a href="http://www.facebook.com/uclcsml">CSML on Facebook</a>, '
         b'follow <a href="https://twitter.com/#!/uclcsml"><tt>@uclcsml</tt></a'
         b'> and spread the word!\n</p>\n\n</div>\n\n<div class="news">\n<h3>'
         b'<a href="/news/2012-02-20-collaboration-ism">Collaboration between I'
         b'SM and CSML</a></h3>\n<p>\n<img src="/userdata/news_images/ism_sig'
         b'ning.jpg" width="250" style="float:right;" />\r\nThe <a href="http'
         b'://www.ism.ac.jp/index_e.html">Institute of Statistical Mathematics '
         b'(ISM)</a> in Tokyo and CSML have signed an agreement to undertake ac'
         b'ademic and collaboration to develop mutually beneficial, creative an'
         b'd productive scholarly activities in the field of statistical machin'
         b'e learning. Professor Shiro Ikeda from ISM visited UCL this week to '
         b'officially sign the agreement, here seen with the Dean of MAPS Richa'
         b'rd Catlow, <a href="/people/silva">Ricardo Silva</a> and <a href="/p'
         b'eople/girolami">Mark Girolami</a> both from CSML. This is an importa'
         b'nt agreement and opens a number of new developing collaborations bet'
         b'ween UCL and ISM.\r\n</p><p>\r\nOne collaboration currently underway'
         b' is on the application of kernel methods from machine learning to pr'
         b'oblems in statistics (hypothesis testing and Bayesian inference), un'
         b'dertaken by Professor Fukumizu at the department of statistical mode'
         b'lling at ISM, and <a href="/people/gretton">Arthur Gretton</a> at th'
         b'e Gatsby Unit.\n</p>\n\n</div>\n\n</div>\n\n\t\t\t\t\t<div id="ie_cl'
